{
  "title": "Institutionalisierung des Loyalismus",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ec8535cf7e83a33d",
      "text": "Putin's integration function, however, is not based solely on the abundance of presidential power, but above all on an informal patronage system with whose help he governs. The \"institutionalization of loyalism \"53 began as early as his inauguration, when Putin brought his own rope team from Petersburg, where he had begun his political career, to Moscow and installed it there.54 Part of this project was also to assure overconfident 'oligarchs' of the validity of the \"vertical of power,\" which was the purpose of, among other things, the show trial of Mikhail Khodorkovsky in 2003.55 Putin also turned on those who had helped support his rise in order to teach the system's profiteers and \"super-rich\" a lesson.56 This promoted the spirit of subservience within the vertical of power immensely57 because from now on the various factions of the elite, which are to be understood as informal actors, knew that battles of demarcation and the assertion of particular interests could be waged solely with the president in mind and centered on his actions.58 \"Parallel to the autocratic power vertical, oligarchic forms of rule have established themselves in the Putin system. In these structures, which are concealed from the outside world, the president's mandarins vie for influence and ownership. The new oligarchs are at the head of various informal 'influence groups,' ... Putin's co-rulers and confidants form the 'inner circle,' or the Kremlin's secret cabinet. It consists of about 12 to 15 people ... While all members of the collective are closely bound to the president by their personal loyalty, they and their respective networks compete with each other in a more or less covert manner. \"59 The informal groups interact with and against each other dynamically and without any rules of the game60 so that it is up to the president to organize a balance of interests that corresponds to his ideas.61 "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6923cd9b9e04a9ad",
      "text": "The basis for this is the economy of a petro- and natural gas state, a \"commodity appendage of the world community, \"62 which is not competitive as a commodity-producing society. A study published in 2011 by the World Economic Forum, for example, put the productivity of the Russian Federation at only about half that of the countries organized in the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).63 According to the study, there is no improvement in sight: \"Although the shrinking of the manufacturing sectors is a process that most transition economies have undergone, the decline of Russian manufacturing beyond the initial transition period remains a worrying trend for a number of reasons. The most important is that, while the number of jobs in manufacturing is declining, employment in the government sector is growing, pointing to a move toward a growing role of the state that is built on the redistribution of resources rather than creation of value. \"64 While Putin decrees his ideal of the \"supercentralized state\" as genetically given by nature and standing in the tradition of the \"Russian people, \"65 it has become clear in the course of his presidency that he considers democratic political competition and free media \"incompatible with the primary goal of Russia's economic consolidation. \"66 Critics have rightly called the media \"Gleichschaltung,\" or \"bringing them into line. \"67 In any case, constant intimidation, restriction and arbitrariness are part of the demonstrable repertoire of media policy under Putin.68 This goes hand in hand with the consistent transformation of the political landscape into a one-party system,69 embodied by Putin's party \"Edinaja Rossija\" (United Russia)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0399c4c98c41a4c5",
      "text": "Patriotism and nationalism play an important role and were at times also decisively promoted by the two youth organizations Nashi (Ours) and Idushchev Vmeste (Common Path), which are unconditionally loyal to Putin.70 They were primarily established to counteract the emergence of diffuse democracy movements and 'color revolutions' such as those in Georgia and Ukraine.71 However, they failed to attract young people and organize them into conformist structures to the desired extent, which is why financial support for both has since ceased and they have degenerated into irrelevance.72 Agitation and targeted campaigns against certain ethnic groups (\"Caucasians\"), homosexuals, and supposedly extra-Russian actors and \"agents,\" as well as the staging of espionage scandals, are used \"to mobilize society by searching for an enemy. \"73 Russian-style nationalism and ethnocentrism74 find expression in the community ideology of a 'Eurasian movement' promoted by Putin, which is set against the liberalism identified as Western and which contrasts the positive connotation of the \"whole\" with the minor importance of the individual.75 The National Bolshevik and fascist Alexandr Dugin76 , one of the intellectual fathers of the contemporary remake of Russian-Eurasian ideology, also advises Vladimir Putin, although there are divergent assessments of Dugin's actual influence on the president.77"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e6ce8776d4c9c617",
      "text": "The search for the enemy within is supplemented by the fight against external enemies. Not only the stirring up of anti-Western sentiment,78 but also military interventions such as those in Georgia, Ukraine, and most recently in Syria serve not least to consolidate the regime internally, as [[Robert Horvath]] makes clear: \"Most of the Kremlin's counter-measures were directed at the pacification of the domestic political landscape: the subjugation of opposition institutions, the consolidation of elites under the banner of a state ideology, and the mobilization of support through organizations such as Nashi. \"79 Horvath therefore also speaks aptly of Putin's \"preventive counterrevolution. \"80"
